<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-182-576  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 182 576.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Feb 26 1990 v7 n8 p133(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MCA patent holder out of luck. (Computer Automation Inc findsMicro Channel Architecture patents ignored)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burke, Steven.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Computer Automation Inc. (patents).andO;Ticker:    CAUT.andO;Topic:     Micro Channel ArchitecturePatentComputer DesignBusesHardware Vendors.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Steven BurkeandM;Two years after it began trying to strong-arm Micro Channel product vendorsinto signing patent licensing agreements, Computer Automation Inc.'s bark isstill worse than its bite.andM;The Irvine, Calif., firm, which claims to own key patents on the MicroChannel memory-addressing scheme, has persuaded only three computer makers toante up and pay patent licensing fees.andP;  And last week, it reported a loss of$561,000 on sales of $1.3 million for the quarter ended Dec.andP;  31.andM;The small, relatively unknown maker of automatic test equipment stunned thePC industry in January 1988 by revealing that it had signed a royaltylicensing agreement with IBM relating to the automatic memory-addressingcapability of the PS/2's Micro Channel architecture (MCA).andM;After that announcement, some PC and board makers feared they would have topay royalties to Computer Automation to produce a Micro Channel product.andM;But since then, Computer Automation has revealed that only a Taiwanesecomputer maker, which it refused to name, and Canon of Japan have signedsimilar licensing agreements.andP;  IBM has paid Computer Automation more than$500,000 since the agreement was signed in 1987, according to ComputerAutomation Chairman George Pratt.andM;Pratt believes that Computer Automation's poor balance sheet is responsible,in part, for companies refusing to sign agreements.andM;IBM has acknowledged it signed a cross-licensing deal with ComputerAutomation.andP;  But an IBM spokeswoman, Linda Dezan, in White Plains, N.Y., saidComputer Automation's patents provide an &quot;ease-of-use feature that is notessential to the architecture.&quot;andM;Martin Alpert, chairman of Cumulus Corp., a Cleveland maker of PS/2 MicroChannel add-on boards, said the Computer Automation patents do not appear tobe an issue at this point for the industry.andM;Pratt said Computer Automation will become more aggressive about pursuingcompanies infringing on the Computer Automation patents in the next quarter.andO;He said his message to such companies is, &quot;You'll be hearing from us.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>